VALUES
(42, 4, 28, 44, 7, 54, 54, 'filled with wrath', 'Emotional Reactions to Messages', 'Both passages emphasize strong emotional responses to challenging messages. In Luke, the synagogue''s wrath parallels the anger expressed in Acts, where the listeners are described as being cut to the heart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 29, 43, 8, 59, 59, NULL, 'Attempts to Harm Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility Jesus faced from those in authority. In Luke, the crowd seeks to cast him down, while in John, they attempt to stone him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 29, 4, 15, 35, 35, 'cast him down headlong', 'Rejection and Punishment Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rejection leading to punishment. In Luke, the crowd seeks to cast Jesus down, while in Numbers, the punishment for sin is death by stoning.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 29, 19, 37, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Violence Against the Innocent', 'This connection highlights the theme of violence against the righteous. Both passages depict the wicked seeking to harm the innocent, as seen in the intent to ''cast down'' in Luke and the actions of the wicked in Psalms.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 29, 19, 37, 32, 33, NULL, 'Connection of Righteousness and Persecution', 'This connection highlights the theme of the wicked seeking to harm the righteous, as seen in both passages. In Luke, the crowd attempts to cast Jesus down, paralleling the wicked''s intent in Psalms to slay the righteous.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 29, 43, 8, 37, 37, NULL, 'Rejection and Threat of Violence', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by Jesus in both passages. In Luke, the crowd seeks to cast Jesus down, while in John, they seek to kill him, indicating a growing hostility towards his message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 29, 44, 7, 57, 58, NULL, 'Rejection and Violence Against Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the act of casting someone out of the city as a response to their message. In Luke, Jesus is thrust out, while in Acts, Stephen is cast out and stoned, illustrating a pattern of violent rejection of prophetic figures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 29, 44, 16, 23, 24, NULL, 'Rejection and Imprisonment Motif', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rejection and physical restraint. In Luke, Jesus is thrust out of the city, while in Acts, Paul and Silas are cast into prison.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 30, 43, 10, 39, 39, NULL, 'Escape from Danger', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of Jesus escaping from those who sought to harm him. In Luke 4:30, he ''went his way,'' while in John 10:39, he ''escaped out of their hand.''', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 30, 43, 8, 59, 59, 'through the midst of them', 'Jesus Passing Through the Crowd', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus navigating hostile situations. Both passages emphasize Jesus moving ''through the midst of them'' to escape danger.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 30, 43, 18, 6, 7, NULL, 'Jesus'' Authority and Escape', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority in the face of opposition. In Luke, he passes through a hostile crowd unharmed, while in John, his declaration causes those seeking him to fall back, showcasing his power.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 30, 44, 12, 18, 18, NULL, 'Escape and Disappearance Motif', 'This connection highlights the theme of escape in both passages. In Luke 4:30, Jesus passes through a crowd unharmed, while in Acts 12:18, there is confusion among soldiers about Peter''s disappearance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 31, 40, 4, 13, 13, 'Capernaum, a city of Galilee', 'Capernaum as Jesus'' Teaching Base', 'Both passages emphasize Capernaum as a significant location for Jesus'' ministry. Luke highlights his teaching there, while Matthew notes his dwelling in the city, indicating its importance in his early work.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 31, 41, 1, 21, 28, 'taught them on the sabbath days', 'Teaching on the Sabbath', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching on the sabbath in Capernaum. This connection highlights the authority with which he taught, as noted in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 31, 40, 10, 23, 23, NULL, 'Teaching and Movement in Cities', 'This connection highlights the theme of movement between cities in both passages. In Luke, Jesus teaches in Capernaum, while in Matthew, the instruction to flee to another city emphasizes the ongoing mission of spreading his teachings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 31, 44, 14, 6, 7, NULL, 'Preaching in Cities', 'This connection highlights the theme of preaching in cities. Both passages mention specific cities where teaching and preaching occur, emphasizing the spread of the message in urban areas.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 31, 42, 4, 23, 23, 'Capernaum', 'Connection Between Capernaum Teachings', 'This connection highlights the significance of Capernaum as a place where Jesus taught and performed miracles. Both passages emphasize the expectation of miraculous works in Capernaum, linking the teachings in the city to the broader context of Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 32, 42, 4, 36, 36, 'his word was with power', 'Authority and Power in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the authority and power of Jesus'' words. In Luke 4:32, his doctrine astonishes the listeners, while in Luke 4:36, they recognize his command over unclean spirits as authoritative and powerful.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 32, 40, 7, 28, 29, 'astonished at his doctrine', 'Authority in Jesus'' Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the astonishment of the people at Jesus'' doctrine. They highlight his authoritative teaching style, contrasting it with that of the scribes.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 32, 43, 6, 63, 63, 'his word was with power', 'Power of Words in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' words, emphasizing their power and life-giving nature. Both passages convey that His teachings are not merely intellectual but carry spiritual vitality.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 32, 47, 10, 4, 5, 'his word was with power', 'Power of God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the theme of power in both passages. Luke emphasizes the authority of Jesus'' teachings, while 2 Corinthians speaks of the mighty weapons through God that can dismantle strongholds, suggesting a shared focus on divine power in spiritual matters.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 32, 56, 2, 15, 15, 'with power', 'Authority in Teaching', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in teaching. Both passages emphasize the power and authority behind the spoken word, with Luke noting the astonishment at Jesus'' doctrine and Titus urging the speaker to exhort and rebuke with authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 32, 58, 4, 12, 13, 'his word was with power', 'Power of God''s Word', 'Both passages emphasize the power of God''s word. Luke highlights the astonishment at Jesus'' doctrine, while Hebrews describes the word of God as ''quick, and powerful.'' This connection highlights the transformative and penetrating nature of divine communication.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 32, 52, 1, 5, 5, 'with power', 'Power of the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of power associated with the word of God. Luke highlights the astonishment at Jesus'' doctrine being ''with power,'' while 1 Thessalonians speaks of the gospel coming ''in power.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 33, 41, 1, 23, 23, NULL, 'Connection of Unclean Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize a man with an unclean spirit who cries out in a synagogue. This parallel highlights the similar narrative of Jesus confronting evil spirits in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 34, 41, 1, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Demonic Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as ''the Holy One of God'' by unclean spirits. This connection highlights the authority of Jesus over evil forces in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 34, 40, 8, 29, 29, 'what have we to do with thee', 'Demons Recognizing Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the demons'' recognition of Jesus'' authority and identity as the Son of God. They express fear of His power and question His intentions regarding their fate.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 34, 59, 2, 19, 19, 'thou Jesus of Nazareth? art thou come to destroy us?', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus'' identity as ''the Holy One of God'' in Luke, paralleling James'' assertion that even ''the devils also believe.'' Both passages emphasize the recognition of divine authority and the response of fear or trembling.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 34, 42, 1, 35, 35, 'the Holy One of God', 'Connection of the Holy One', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''the Holy One of God.'' In Luke 4:34, a demon recognizes Jesus'' divine nature, while Luke 1:35 refers to Jesus as ''that holy thing'' born of Mary, linking their holiness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 34, 44, 3, 14, 14, 'the Holy One of God', 'Connection of the Holy One', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as the ''Holy One.'' In Luke, a demon recognizes Jesus'' divine nature, while in Acts, Peter refers to Jesus as ''the Holy One'' to highlight the people''s rejection of Him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
